\begin_layout Standard
Note that the algorithm requires some initial point 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,s)$
\end_inset

 close to the central path and we will show how to get this in the next section (by changing the linear program temporarily).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First,
 we show that the invariant is maintained in each step.
 The conclusion that the distance is less than 
\begin_inset Formula $t/6$
\end_inset

 is needed in Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:find_IPM_interior"

\end_inset

,
 where we call 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathtt{L2Step}$
\end_inset

 on a modified LP and then prove that the result is close to the central path for the original LP.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:L2Step"

\end_inset

Suppose that the input satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,s)\in\PriR^{\circ}\times\DualR^{\circ}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\|xs-t_{\mathrm{start}}\mathbf{1}\|_{2}\leq\frac{t_{\mathrm{start}}}{4}$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
 the algorithm 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathtt{L2Step}$
\end_inset

 maintains 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,s)\in\PriR^{\circ}\times\DualR^{\circ}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\|xs-t\mathbf{1}\|_{2}\leq\frac{t}{6}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We prove by induction that 
\begin_inset Formula $\|xs-t\mathbf{1}\|_{2}\leq\frac{t}{6}$
\end_inset

 after each step.
 Note that the input satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\|xs-t\mathbf{1}\|_{2}\leq\frac{t}{4}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x'=x+\delta_{x}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $s'=s+\delta_{s}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $t'$
\end_inset

 be as defined in the algorithm.
 Note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x's'-t'\mathbf{1}=(x+\delta_{x})(s+\delta_{s})-t'\mathbf{1}=\mu+\ms\delta_{x}+\mx\delta_{s}+\delta_{x}\delta_{s}-t'\mathbf{1}.
\]

\end_inset

Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:Newton_step"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ms\delta_{x}+\mx\delta_{s}=t'\mathbf{1}-\mu$
\end_inset

.
 Hence,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x's'-t'\mathbf{1}=\delta_{x}\delta_{s}=\mx^{-1}\delta_{x}\cdot\ms^{-1}\delta_{s}\cdot\mu.
\]

\end_inset

Using this,
 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\|x's'-t'\mathbf{1}\|_{2}\leq\|\mu^{1/2}\mx^{-1}\delta_{x}\|_{2}\|\mu^{1/2}\ms^{-1}\delta_{s}\|_{2}=\|\mx^{-1}\delta_{x}\|_{\mu}\|\ms^{-1}\delta_{s}\|_{\mu}\leq\|\delta_{\mu}/\mu\|^{2}_{\mu}.
\]

\end_inset

Here we used Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:Projection_property"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 at the end.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Using 
\begin_inset Formula $t'\mathbf{1}-\mu=\frac{t'}{t}(t\mathbf{1}-\mu)+(\frac{t'}{t}-1)\mu$
\end_inset

,
 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\|\delta_{\mu}/\mu\|_{\mu}=\|\frac{t'}{t}\frac{t\mathbf{1}-\mu}{\mu}+(\frac{t'}{t}-1)\|_{\mu}\leq\frac{t'}{t}\|xs-t\mathbf{1}\|_{\mu^{-1}}+\|\frac{t'}{t}-1\|_{\mu}.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\mu-t\mathbf{1}\|_{2}\leq\frac{t}{4}$
\end_inset

,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\min_{i}\mu_{i}\geq\frac{3t}{4}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\max_{i}\mu_{i}\leq\frac{5}{4}t$
\end_inset

.
 Using 
\begin_inset Formula $|\frac{t'}{t}-1|\leq h=\frac{1}{16\sqrt{n}}$
\end_inset

,
 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\|\delta_{\mu}/\mu\|_{\mu}\leq\frac{t'}{t}\sqrt{\frac{4}{3t}}\|xs-t\mathbf{1}\|_{2}+h\sqrt{\frac{5}{4}tn}\leq\sqrt{\frac{t}{12}}+h\sqrt{\frac{5}{4}tn}\leq0.36\sqrt{t}.
\]

\end_inset

Hence,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\|x's'-t'\mathbf{1}\|_{2}\leq\|\delta_{\mu}/\mu\|^{2}_{\mu}\leq0.13t\leq t'/6$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\delta_{\mu}/\mu\|^{2}_{\mu}<\min_{i}\mu_{i}$
\end_inset

,
 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $(x',s')$
\end_inset

 is feasible (Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:step_size"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the lemma above only concludes that the output is close to the central path.
 To upper bound the error,
 we can apply Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:duality_gap"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 which shows the duality gap is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\top}s$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Finding a feasible interior point by lifting
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:find_IPM_interior"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here we discuss how to get a feasible interior point close to the central path by modifying the linear program.
 The runtime of an interior point method depends on how degenerate the linear program is.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:LP_para"

\end_inset

We define the following parameters for the linear program 
\begin_inset Formula $\min_{\ma x=b,x\geq0}c^{\top}x$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Inner radius 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

:
 There exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\PriR$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\geq r$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in[n]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Outer radius 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

:
 For any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\geq0$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\ma x=b$
\end_inset

,
 we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\|x\|_{2}\leq R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Lipschitz constant 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\|c\|_{2}\leq L$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathtt{L2Step}$
\end_inset

 requires a feasible point near the central path,
 we modify the linear program to make it happen.
 To satisfy the constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $\ma x=b$
\end_inset

,
 we start the algorithm by taking a least-squares solution of the constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $\ma x=b$
\end_inset

.
 Since this solution can be negative,
 we write the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x=x^{+}-x^{-}$
\end_inset

 with both 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{+},x^{-}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 We put a large cost vector on 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{-}$
\end_inset

 to ensure the solution is roughly the same.
 The crux of the proof is that if we optimize this new program well enough,
 we will have 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{+}-x^{-}>0$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{+}-x^{-}$
\end_inset

 gives a good starting point for the original program.
 For technical reasons,
 we need to put an extra constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $1^{\top}x^{+}\leq\Lambda$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 to ensure the problem is bounded.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:modified_LP_construction"

\end_inset

Given a linear program 
\begin_inset Formula $\min_{\ma x=b,x\in\R^{n}_{\geq0}}c^{\top}x$
\end_inset

 with inner radius 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

,
 outer radius 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and Lipschitz constant 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and any 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq\eta\leq\frac{1}{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the following modified linear program:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\min_{(x^{+},x^{-},x^{\theta})\in\PriR_{\eta}}\left\langle c^{+},x^{+}\right\rangle +\left\langle c^{-},x^{-}\right\rangle 
\]

\end_inset

with
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\PriR_{\eta}=\left\{ (x^{+},x^{-},x^{\theta})\in\R^{2n+1}_{\geq0}:\ \ma(x^{+}-x^{-})=b,\sum^{n}_{i=1}x^{+}_{i}+x^{\theta}=\widetilde{b}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{R}=6R/\eta$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{t}=6000n^{2}R/(\eta^{2}r)\cdot LR$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ox^{+}=\overline{t}/(c+\overline{t}/\overline{R})$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ox^{-}=\ox^{+}-\ma^{\top}(\ma\ma^{\top})^{-1}b$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{+}=c$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{-}=\overline{t}/\ox^{-}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{b}=\sum^{n}_{i=1}\ox^{+}_{i}+\overline{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
 we have that
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $(\ox^{+},\ox^{-},\overline{R})$
\end_inset

 is on the central path of the modified program at 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For any primal 
\begin_inset Formula $x\defeq(x^{+},x^{-},x^{\theta})\in\PriR_{\eta}$
\end_inset

 and dual 
\begin_inset Formula $s\defeq(s^{+},s^{-},s^{\theta})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{5}{6}LR\leq x_{i}s_{i}\leq\frac{7}{6}LR$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

,
 we have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x^{+}-x^{-},s^{+}-s^{\theta})\in\PriR\times\DualR
\]

\end_inset

and that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{-}_{i}\leq\eta x^{+}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{\theta}\leq\eta s^{+}_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
We continue from the discussion in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:SolveLP_apx"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We first show that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\ox^{+},\ox^{-},\overline{R})$
\end_inset

 defined in Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:modified_LP_construction"

\end_inset

 is indeed on the central path of the modified linear program.
 We define the dual of the modified linear program as follows
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{D}_{\eta}=\{(s^{+},s^{-},s^{\theta})\in\R^{2n+1}_{\geq0}:\ma^{\top}y+\lambda\mathbf{1}+s^{+}=c^{+},-\ma^{\top}y+s^{-}=c^{-},\lambda+s^{\theta}=0\text{ for some }y\in\R^{d}\text{ and }\lambda\in\R\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:ipm_interior_modified"

\end_inset

The modified linear program in Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:modified_LP_construction"

\end_inset

 has an explicit point on the central path,
\begin_inset Formula $(\ox^{+},\ox^{-},\overline{R})$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Recall that we say 
\begin_inset Formula $(x^{+},x^{-},x^{\theta})$
\end_inset

 is on the central path at 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{+},x^{-},x^{\theta}$
\end_inset

 are positive,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{+}_{i}s^{+}_{i}=t,x^{-}_{i}s^{-}_{i}=t,x^{\theta}s^{\theta}=t$
\end_inset

 and the following equations hold
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\ma x^{+}-\ma x^{-} & =b,\nonumber \\
\sum^{n}_{i=1}x^{+}_{i}+x^{\theta} & =\widetilde{b},\nonumber \\
\ma^{\top}y+\lambda+s^{+} & =c^{+},\label{eq:KKT_modified_LP}\\
-\ma^{\top}y+s^{-} & =c^{-},\nonumber \\
\lambda+s^{\theta} & =0,\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{+},s^{-}\in\R^{n}_{>0}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{\theta}>0$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\R^{d}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Now,
 we verify the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\ox^{+}=\overline{t}/(c+\overline{t}/\overline{R})$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ox^{-}=\ox^{+}-\ma^{\top}(\ma\ma^{\top})^{-1}b$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ox^{\theta}=\overline{R}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $y=0$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\os^{+}=\overline{t}/\ox^{+}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\os^{-}=\overline{t}/\ox^{-}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\os^{\theta}=\overline{t}/\ox^{\theta}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=-\os^{\theta}$
\end_inset

.
 Using 
\begin_inset Formula $\ma\ma^{\top}(\ma\ma^{\top})^{-1}b=b$
\end_inset

,
 one can check that it satisfies all the equality constraints above.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
For the positivity constraints,
 using 
\begin_inset Formula $\|c\|_{\infty}\leq L$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{t}\geq4L\overline{R}$
\end_inset

,
 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{4}{5}\overline{R}\leq\frac{\overline{t}}{L+\overline{t}/\overline{R}}\leq\ox^{+}_{i}\leq\frac{\overline{t}}{-L+\overline{t}/\overline{R}}\leq\frac{4}{3}\overline{R}\label{eq:x_pos_bound}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\ox^{+}>0$
\end_inset

 and so is 
\begin_inset Formula $\os^{+}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\circ}\defeq\ma^{\top}(\ma\ma^{\top})^{-1}b$
\end_inset

 is the least-squares solution to 
\begin_inset Formula $\ma x=b$
\end_inset

,
 so,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\|x_{\circ}\|_{2}\leq\|x^{*}\|_{2}\leq R<\frac{1}{4}\overline{R}.\label{eq:x0_upper_bound}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Together with 
\begin_inset Formula $\ox^{+}_{i}\geq\frac{4}{5}\overline{R}$
\end_inset

,
 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ox^{-}_{i}\geq\frac{4}{5}\overline{R}-\frac{1}{4}\overline{R}>0
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 Hence,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ox^{-}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\os^{-}$
\end_inset

 are positive.
 Finally,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ox^{\theta}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\os^{\theta}$
\end_inset

 are positive.
 This proves that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\ox^{+},\ox^{-},\overline{R})$
\end_inset

 is on the central path at 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next,
 we show that the near-central-path point 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,s)$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=LR$
\end_inset

 is far from the boundary 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{+}=0$
\end_inset

 and is close to the boundary 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{-}=0$
\end_inset

.
 The proofs of both statements use the same idea:
 the optimality condition of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Throughout the rest of the proof,
 we are given 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,s)\in\PriR_{\eta}\times\mathcal{D}_{\eta}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=xs$
\end_inset

 satisfies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{5}{6}LR\leq\mu\leq\frac{7}{6}LR.
\]

\end_inset

We write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 into its three parts 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mu^{+},\mu^{-},\mu^{\theta})$
\end_inset

.
 By Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:primal_dual_representation"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\defeq(x^{+},x^{-},x^{\theta})$
\end_inset

 minimizes the function
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{\mu}(x^{+},x^{-},x^{\theta})\defeq\left\langle c^{+},x^{+}\right\rangle +\left\langle c^{-},x^{-}\right\rangle -\sum^{n}_{i=1}\mu^{+}_{i}\log x^{+}_{i}-\sum^{n}_{i=1}\mu^{-}_{i}\log x^{-}_{i}-\mu^{\theta}\log x^{\theta}
\]

\end_inset

over the domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\PriR_{\eta}$
\end_inset

.
 The gradient of 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is somewhat complicated.
 We avoid it by considering the directional derivative at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 along a feasible direction toward a lifted version of a point 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ma v=b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v\geq r$
\end_inset

.
 Since our domain is in 
\begin_inset Formula $\PriR_{\eta}\subset\R^{2n+1}$
\end_inset

,
 we lift 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 to the higher-dimensional point defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
v^{-} & =\min(x^{-},\frac{4L\overline{R}}{\overline{t}}\cdot R),\\
v^{+} & =v+v^{-},\\
v^{\theta} & =\widetilde{b}-\sum^{n}_{i=1}v^{+}_{i}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

First,
 we need to get some basic bounds on 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{b}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{-}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:ipm_propert_modified"

\end_inset

We have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{4}{5}n\overline{R}\leq\widetilde{b}\leq3n\overline{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{-}_{i}\geq3\overline{t}/(7\overline{R})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
By 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:x_pos_bound"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{4}{5}\overline{R}\leq\ox^{+}_{i}\leq\frac{4}{3}\overline{R}$
\end_inset

.
 By the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{b}$
\end_inset

,
 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{b}=\sum^{n}_{i=1}\ox^{+}_{i}+\overline{R}\leq\frac{4}{3}n\overline{R}+\overline{R}\leq3n\overline{R}.
\]

\end_inset

Similarly,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{b}=\sum_{i}\ox^{+}_{i}+\overline{R}\geq\frac{4}{5}n\overline{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
For the bound on 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{-}_{i}$
\end_inset

,
 recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{-}_{i}=\overline{t}/\ox^{-}_{i}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\ox^{-}=\ox^{+}-x_{\circ}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\circ}=\ma^{\top}(\ma\ma^{\top})^{-1}b$
\end_inset

.
 Using 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:x0_upper_bound"

\end_inset

,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ox^{-}_{i}\leq\frac{4}{3}\overline{R}+R.
\]

\end_inset

Therefore,
 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{-}\geq3\overline{t}/(7\overline{R})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following lemma shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $(v^{+},v^{-},v^{\theta})\in\PriR_{\eta}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:IPM_exact_inner_pt"

\end_inset

We have that 
\begin_inset Formula $(v^{+},v^{-},v^{\theta})\in\PriR_{\eta}$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\theta}\geq\frac{1}{2}n\overline{R}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $(v^{+},v^{-},v^{\theta})$
\end_inset

 satisfies the linear constraints of 
\begin_inset Formula $\PriR_{\eta}$
\end_inset

 by construction.
 It suffices to prove that the vector is positive.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{-}>0$
\end_inset

,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{-}>0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $v\geq r$
\end_inset

,
 we also have 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{+}>0$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\theta}$
\end_inset

,
 we use 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{b}\geq\frac{4}{5}n\overline{R}$
\end_inset

 (Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:ipm_propert_modified"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}\leq R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{-}\leq\frac{4L\overline{R}}{t}\cdot R\leq R$
\end_inset

 to get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
v^{+}_{i}=v_{i}+v^{-}_{i}\leq2R\label{eq:v_plus_upper}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and hence
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
v^{\theta}=\widetilde{b}-\sum^{n}_{i=1}v^{+}_{i} & \geq\frac{4}{5}n\overline{R}-\sum^{n}_{i=1}(v_{i}+v^{-}_{i})\geq\frac{1}{2}n\overline{R}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next,
 we define the path 
\begin_inset Formula $p(\tau)=(1-\tau)(x^{+},x^{-},x^{\theta})+\tau(v^{+},v^{-},v^{\theta})$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p(0)$
\end_inset

 minimizes 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\mu}$
\end_inset

,
 we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d}{d\tau}f_{\mu}(p(\tau))|_{\tau=0}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 In particular,
 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
0 & \leq\frac{d}{d\tau}f_{\mu}(p(\tau))|_{\tau=0}\nonumber \\
 & =\left\langle c,v^{+}-x^{+}\right\rangle +\left\langle c^{-},v^{-}-x^{-}\right\rangle -\sum^{n}_{i=1}\frac{\mu^{+}_{i}}{x^{+}_{i}}(v^{+}-x^{+})_{i}-\sum^{n}_{i=1}\frac{\mu^{-}_{i}}{x^{-}_{i}}(v^{-}-x^{-})_{i}-\frac{\mu^{\theta}}{x^{\theta}}(v^{\theta}-x^{\theta})\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{\mu^{\theta}}{x^{\theta}}(x^{\theta}-v^{\theta})+\sum^{n}_{i=1}(c_{i}-\frac{\mu^{+}_{i}}{x^{+}_{i}})(v^{+}-x^{+})_{i}+\sum^{n}_{i=1}(c^{-}_{i}-\frac{\mu^{-}_{i}}{x^{-}_{i}})(v^{-}-x^{-})_{i}.\label{eq:LP_exact_3_term}
\end{align}

\end_inset

We now bound the three terms.
 For the first term,
 we note that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\mu^{\theta}}{x^{\theta}}(x^{\theta}-v^{\theta})\leq\mu^{\theta}\leq2LR.\label{eq:LP_exact_3_term_1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For the second term in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:LP_exact_3_term"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 we have the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:LP_exact_3_term_1"

\end_inset

We have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum^{n}_{i=1}(c_{i}-\frac{\mu^{+}_{i}}{x^{+}_{i}})(v^{+}-x^{+})_{i}\leq4nLR-\frac{LRr}{2\min_{i}x^{+}_{i}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sum^{n}_{i=1}(c_{i}-\frac{\mu^{+}_{i}}{x^{+}_{i}})(v^{+}-x^{+})_{i} & =\sum^{n}_{i=1}(c_{i}v^{+}_{i}-\frac{\mu^{+}_{i}}{x^{+}_{i}}v^{+}_{i}-c_{i}x^{+}_{i}+\mu^{+}_{i})\\
 & \leq\sum^{n}_{i=1}c_{i}v^{+}_{i}+\sum^{n}_{i=1}\mu^{+}_{i}-\sum^{n}_{i=1}\frac{\mu^{+}_{i}}{x^{+}_{i}}v^{+}_{i}\\
 & \leq\|c\|_{\infty}\|v^{+}\|_{1}+2nLR-\frac{1}{2}\sum^{n}_{i=1}\frac{LRr}{x^{+}_{i}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we used 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu^{+}_{i}\in[\frac{LR}{2},2LR]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{+}_{i}\geq v_{i}\geq r$
\end_inset

 at the end.
 The result follows from 
\begin_inset Formula $\|c\|_{\infty}\leq L$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\|v^{+}\|_{1}\leq2nR$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:v_plus_upper"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the third term in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:LP_exact_3_term"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 we have the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:LP_exact_3_term_2"

\end_inset

We have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum^{n}_{i=1}(c^{-}_{i}-\frac{\mu^{-}_{i}}{x^{-}_{i}})(v^{-}-x^{-})_{i}\leq\frac{1}{2}LR-\frac{\overline{t}}{8\overline{R}}\max_{i}x^{-}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Using 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{-}=\min(x^{-},\frac{4L\overline{R}}{\overline{t}}\cdot R)$
\end_inset

,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{-}_{i}\leq x^{-}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 We can ignore the terms with 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{-}_{i}=x^{-}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
For 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{-}_{i}<x^{-}_{i}$
\end_inset

,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{-}_{i}\geq\frac{4L\overline{R}}{\overline{t}}R$
\end_inset

.
 Using 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{-}_{i}\geq3\overline{t}/(7\overline{R})$
\end_inset

 (Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:ipm_propert_modified"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c^{-}_{i}-\frac{\mu^{-}_{i}}{x^{-}_{i}}\geq c^{-}_{i}-\frac{\mu^{-}_{i}}{\frac{4L\overline{R}}{\overline{t}}R}\geq c^{-}_{i}-\frac{\frac{7}{6}LR}{\frac{4L\overline{R}}{\overline{t}}R}=c^{-}_{i}-\frac{7\overline{t}}{24\overline{R}}\geq\frac{\overline{t}}{8\overline{R}}.
\]

\end_inset

Hence,
 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum^{n}_{i=1}(c^{-}_{i}-\frac{\mu^{-}_{i}}{x^{-}_{i}})(v^{-}-x^{-})_{i}\leq\frac{\overline{t}}{8\overline{R}}\sum^{n}_{i=1}(v^{-}-x^{-})_{i}\leq\frac{\overline{t}}{8\overline{R}}(\frac{4L\overline{R}}{\overline{t}}\cdot R-\max_{i}x^{-}_{i}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Combining 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:LP_exact_3_term"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:LP_exact_3_term_1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:LP_exact_3_term_1"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:LP_exact_3_term_2"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & \leq\frac{\mu^{\theta}}{x^{\theta}}(x^{\theta}-v^{\theta})+\sum^{n}_{i=1}(c_{i}-\frac{\mu^{+}_{i}}{x^{+}_{i}})(v^{+}-x^{+})_{i}+\sum^{n}_{i=1}(c^{-}_{i}-\frac{\mu^{-}_{i}}{x^{-}_{i}})(v^{-}-x^{-})_{i}\\
 & \leq2LR+4nLR-\frac{LRr}{2\min_{i}x^{+}_{i}}+\frac{1}{2}LR-\frac{\overline{t}}{8\overline{R}}\max_{i}x^{-}_{i}\\
 & \leq6nLR-\frac{LRr}{2\min_{i}x^{+}_{i}}-\frac{\overline{t}}{8\overline{R}}\max_{i}x^{-}_{i}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Hence,
 we show that 
\begin_inset Formula $(x^{+},x^{-},x^{\theta})$
\end_inset

 is close to the central path at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=LR$
\end_inset

 implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\min_{i}x^{+}_{i}$
\end_inset

 cannot be too small and 
\begin_inset Formula $\max_{i}x^{-}_{i}$
\end_inset

 cannot be too large
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{LRr}{2\min_{i}x^{+}_{i}}+\frac{\overline{t}}{8\overline{R}}\max_{i}x^{-}_{i}\leq6nLR.
\]

\end_inset

In particular,
 this shows the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:LP_exact_distance_OPT"

\end_inset

We have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\min_{i}x^{+}_{i}\geq\frac{r}{12n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\max_{i}x^{-}_{i}\leq\frac{48nL\overline{R}}{\overline{t}}\cdot R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now,
 we are ready to prove Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:modified_LP_construction"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Proof of Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:modified_LP_construction"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

First,
 we check 
\begin_inset Formula $x\defeq x^{+}-x^{-}\in\PriR$
\end_inset

.
 By the choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{t}$
\end_inset

,
 Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:LP_exact_distance_OPT"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 shows that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\max_{i}x^{-}_{i}}{\min_{i}x^{+}_{i}}\leq\frac{\frac{48nL\overline{R}}{\overline{t}}\cdot R}{\frac{r}{12n}}=576n^{2}\frac{R}{r}\cdot\frac{L\overline{R}}{\overline{t}}<\eta
\]

\end_inset

Hence,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{+}-x^{-}>0$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ma(x^{+}-x^{-})=b$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Next,
 we check 
\begin_inset Formula $s\defeq s^{+}-s^{\theta}\in\DualR$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\leq R$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{-}_{i}\leq\frac{1}{2}x^{+}_{i}$
\end_inset

,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{+}_{i}\leq2x_{i}\leq2R$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{+}_{i}s^{+}_{i}\geq\frac{5}{6}LR$
\end_inset

,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{+}_{i}\geq\frac{1}{3}L.$
\end_inset

 On the other hand,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\theta}=\widetilde{b}-\sum^{n}_{i=1}x^{+}_{i}\geq\widetilde{b}-2nR\geq\frac{1}{2}n\overline{R}$
\end_inset

 (Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:ipm_propert_modified"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 Hence,
 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{\theta}\leq\frac{\frac{7}{6}LR}{\frac{1}{2}n\overline{R}}\leq\frac{3LR}{n\overline{R}}.$
\end_inset

 Combining both and the choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{R}$
\end_inset

,
 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{s^{\theta}}{\min_{i}s^{+}_{i}}\leq\frac{\frac{3LR}{n\overline{R}}}{L/3}=\frac{9R}{n\overline{R}}<\eta
\]

\end_inset

Hence,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $s=s^{+}-s^{\theta}>0$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ma^{\top}y+s=\ma^{\top}y+s^{+}-s^{\theta}=\ma^{\top}y+s^{+}+\lambda=c$
\end_inset

 (See 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:KKT_modified_LP"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To ensure the reduction does not increase the complexity of solving the linear systems,
 we note that the linear constraint in the modified linear program is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\oma=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
\ma & -\ma & 0\\
1^{\top}_{n} & 0 & 1
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

For any diagonal matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $\mw_{1},\mw_{2}$
\end_inset

 with diagonals 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{1},w_{2}$
\end_inset

 and any scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

,
 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mh\defeq\oma\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
\mw_{1} & 0 & 0\\
0 & \mw_{2} & 0\\
0 & 0 & \alpha
\end{array}\right]\oma^{\top}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\ma(\mw_{1}+\mw_{2})\ma^{\top} & \ma w_{1}\\
(\ma w_{1})^{\top} & \|w_{1}\|_{1}+\alpha
\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset

Note that the second row and second column blocks have size 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 By the block inverse formula,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mh^{-1}v$
\end_inset

 is an explicit formula involving 
\begin_inset Formula $(\ma(\mw_{1}+\mw_{2})\ma^{\top})^{-1}v_{1:d}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(\ma(\mw_{1}+\mw_{2})\ma^{\top})^{-1}\ma w_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence,
 we can compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\mh^{-1}v$
\end_inset

 by solving two linear systems of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\ma\mw\ma^{\top}$
\end_inset

 with some extra linear work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Solving LP Approximately and Exactly
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:SolveLP_apx"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we state our main algorithm.
\end_layout

